# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: structured-logging
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] For computer log management, the **Common Log Format**, also known as the **NCSA Common log format**, (after NCSA HTTPd) is a historically standardized text file format from 2004 that was used by web servers when generating server log files.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] Because the format was standardized, the files had been readily analyzed by a variety of web analysis programs, for example Webalizer and Analog.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] The format is extended by the **Combined Log Format** with referer and user-agent fields.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] A field set to dash (`-`) indicates missing data.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] Log files are a standard tool for computer systems developers and administrators.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] They record the "what happened, when, by whom" of the system.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] This information can record faults and help their diagnosis.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] It can identify security breaches and other computer misuse.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] The information stored is only available for later analysis if it is stored in a form that can be analysed.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] This data can be structured in many ways for analysis.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] For example, storing it in a relational database would force the data into a query-able format.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] However, it would also make it more difficult to retrieve if the computer crashed, and logging would not be available unless the database was available.
[src:structured-logging/common-log-format] A plain text format minimises dependencies on other system processes, and assists logging at all phases of computer operation, including start-up and shut-down, where such processes might be unavailable.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON is a programming language-independent data format.
[src:structured-logging/json] It was derived from JavaScript, but many modern programming languages include code to generate and parse JSON-format data.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON filenames use the extension `.json`.
[src:structured-logging/json] Douglas Crockford originally specified the JSON format in the early 2000s.
[src:structured-logging/json] They and Chip Morningstar sent the first JSON message in April 2001.
[src:structured-logging/json] The 2017 international standard (ECMA-404 and ISO/IEC 21778:2017) specifies that "JSON" is "pronounced /ˈdʒeɪ.sən/, as in 'Jason and The Argonauts'".
[src:structured-logging/json] The first (2013) edition of ECMA-404 did not address the pronunciation.
[src:structured-logging/json] Crockford said in 2011, "There's a lot of argument about how you pronounce that, but I strictly don't care." /ˈdʒeɪˌsɒn/ is another common pronunciation.
[src:structured-logging/json] After RFC 4627 had been available as its "informational" specification since 2006, JSON was first standardized in 2013, as ECMA-404.
[src:structured-logging/json] RFC 8259, published in 2017, is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90, and it remains consistent with ECMA-404.
[src:structured-logging/json] That same year, JSON was also standardized as ISO/IEC 21778:2017.
[src:structured-logging/json] The ECMA and ISO/IEC standards describe only the allowed syntax, whereas the RFC covers some security and interoperability considerations.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON grew out of a need for a real-time server-to-browser session communication protocol without using browser plugins such as Flash or Java applets, the dominant methods used in the early 2000s.
[src:structured-logging/json] Crockford first specified and popularized the JSON format.
[src:structured-logging/json] The acronym originated at State Software, a company cofounded by Crockford and others in March 2001.
[src:structured-logging/json] The cofounders had a round-table discussion and voted on whether to call the data format JSML (JavaScript Markup Language) or JSON (JavaScript Object Notation), as well as under what license type to make it available.
[src:structured-logging/json] The JSON.org website was launched in 2001.
[src:structured-logging/json] In December 2005, Yahoo! began offering some of its Web services in JSON.
[src:structured-logging/json] A precursor to the JSON libraries was used in a children's digital asset trading game project named Cartoon Orbit at Communities.com which used a browser side plug-in with a proprietary messaging format to manipulate DHTML elements.
[src:structured-logging/json] Crockford then found that JavaScript could be used as an object-based messaging format for such a system.
[src:structured-logging/json] The system was sold to Sun Microsystems, Amazon.com, and EDS.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON was based on a subset of the JavaScript scripting language (specifically, Standard ECMA-262 3rd Edition—December 1999) and is commonly used with JavaScript, but it is a language-independent data format.
[src:structured-logging/json] Code for parsing and generating JSON data is readily available in many programming languages.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON's website lists JSON libraries by language.
[src:structured-logging/json] In October 2013, Ecma International published the first edition of its JSON standard ECMA-404.
[src:structured-logging/json] That same year, RFC 7158 used ECMA-404 as a reference.
[src:structured-logging/json] In 2014, RFC 7159 became the main reference for JSON's Internet uses, superseding RFC 4627 and RFC 7158 (but preserving ECMA-262 and ECMA-404 as main references).
[src:structured-logging/json] In November 2017, ISO/IEC JTC 1/SC 22 published ISO/IEC 21778:2017 as an international standard.
[src:structured-logging/json] On December 13, 2017, the Internet Engineering Task Force obsoleted RFC 7159 when it published RFC 8259, which is the current version of the Internet Standard STD 90.
[src:structured-logging/json] Crockford added a clause to the JSON license stating, "The Software shall be used for Good, not Evil", in order to open-source the JSON libraries while mocking corporate lawyers and those who are overly pedantic.
[src:structured-logging/json] On the other hand, this clause led to license compatibility problems of the JSON license with other open-source licenses since open-source software and free software usually imply no restrictions on the purpose of use.
[src:structured-logging/json] The following example shows a possible JSON representation describing a person.
[src:structured-logging/json] This is a consequence of JSON disallowing only "control characters".
[src:structured-logging/json] For maximum portability, these characters are backslash-escaped.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON exchange in an open ecosystem must be encoded in UTF-8.
[src:structured-logging/json] The encoding supports the full Unicode character set, including those characters outside the Basic Multilingual Plane (U+0000 to U+FFFF).
[src:structured-logging/json] However, if escaped, those characters must be written using UTF-16 surrogate pairs.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON became a strict subset of ECMAScript as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:structured-logging/json] Whitespace is allowed and ignored around or between syntactic elements (values and punctuation, but not within a string value).
[src:structured-logging/json] Four specific characters are considered whitespace for this purpose: space, horizontal tab, line feed, and carriage return.
[src:structured-logging/json] In particular, the byte order mark must not be generated by a conforming implementation (though it may be accepted when parsing JSON).
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON does not provide syntax for comments.
[src:structured-logging/json] Early versions of JSON (such as specified by RFC 4627) required that a valid JSON text must consist of only an object or an array type, which could contain other types within them.
[src:structured-logging/json] This restriction was dropped in RFC 7158, where a JSON text was redefined as any serialized value.
[src:structured-logging/json] Numbers in JSON are agnostic with regard to their representation within programming languages.
[src:structured-logging/json] While this allows for numbers of arbitrary precision to be serialized, it may lead to portability issues.
[src:structured-logging/json] For example, since no differentiation is made between integer and floating-point values, some implementations may treat `42`, `42.0`, and `4.2E+1` as the same number, while others may not.
[src:structured-logging/json] The JSON standard makes no requirements regarding implementation details such as overflow, underflow, loss of precision, rounding, or signed zeros, but it does recommend expecting no more than IEEE 754 binary64 precision for "good interoperability".
[src:structured-logging/json] There is no inherent precision loss in serializing a machine-level binary representation of a floating-point number (like binary64) into a human-readable decimal representation (like numbers in JSON) and back; there exist published algorithms to do this conversion exactly and optimally.
[src:structured-logging/json] Comments were intentionally excluded from JSON.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON disallows "trailing commas", a comma after the last value inside a data structure.
[src:structured-logging/json] Trailing commas are a common feature of JSON derivatives to improve ease of use.
[src:structured-logging/json] RFC 8259 describes certain aspects of JSON syntax that, while legal per the specifications, can cause interoperability problems.
[src:structured-logging/json] In 2015, the IETF published RFC 7493, describing the "I-JSON Message Format", a restricted profile of JSON that constrains the syntax and processing of JSON to avoid, as much as possible, these interoperability issues.
[src:structured-logging/json] While JSON provides a syntactic framework for data interchange, unambiguous data interchange also requires agreement between producer and consumer on the semantics of specific use of the JSON syntax.
[src:structured-logging/json] One example of where such an agreement is necessary is the serialization of data types that are not part of the JSON standard, for example, dates and regular expressions.
[src:structured-logging/json] The official MIME type for JSON text is `application/json`, and most modern implementations have adopted this.
[src:structured-logging/json] Legacy MIME types include `text/json`, `text/x-json`, and `text/javascript`.
[src:structured-logging/json] The standard filename extension is .json.
[src:structured-logging/json] The JSON standard does not support object references, but an IETF draft standard for JSON-based object references exists.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON-RPC is a remote procedure call (RPC) protocol built on JSON, as a replacement for XML-RPC or SOAP.
[src:structured-logging/json] It is a simple protocol that defines only a handful of data types and commands.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON-RPC lets a system send notifications (information to the server that does not require a response) and multiple calls to the server that can be answered out of order.
[src:structured-logging/json] Asynchronous JavaScript and JSON (or AJAJ) refers to the same dynamic web page methodology as Ajax, but instead of XML, JSON is the data format.
[src:structured-logging/json] AJAJ is a web development technique that provides for the ability of a web page to request new data after it has loaded into the web browser.
[src:structured-logging/json] Typically, it renders new data from the server in response to user actions on that web page.
[src:structured-logging/json] For example, what the user types into a search box, client-side code then sends to the server, which immediately responds with a drop-down list of matching database items.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON has seen ad hoc usage as a configuration language.
[src:structured-logging/json] In 2012, Douglas Crockford, JSON creator, had this to say about comments in JSON when used as a configuration language: "I know that the lack of comments makes some people sad, but it shouldn't.
[src:structured-logging/json] Suppose you are using JSON to keep configuration files, which you would like to annotate.
[src:structured-logging/json] Go ahead and insert all the comments you like.
[src:structured-logging/json] MongoDB uses JSON-like data for its document-oriented database.
[src:structured-logging/json] Some relational databases have added support for native JSON data types, such as JSONB in PostgreSQL and JSON in MySQL.
[src:structured-logging/json] This allows developers to insert JSON data directly without having to convert it to another format.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON being a subset of JavaScript can lead to the misconception that it is safe to pass JSON texts to the JavaScript `eval()` function.
[src:structured-logging/json] This is not safe, due to certain valid JSON texts, specifically those containing U+2028 LINE SEPARATOR or U+2029 PARAGRAPH SEPARATOR, not being valid JavaScript code until JavaScript specifications were updated in 2019, and so older engines may not support it.
[src:structured-logging/json] To avoid the many pitfalls caused by executing arbitrary code from the Internet, a new function, `JSON.parse()`, was first added to the fifth edition of ECMAScript, which as of 2017 is supported by all major browsers.
[src:structured-logging/json] For non-supported browsers, an API-compatible JavaScript library is provided by Douglas Crockford.
[src:structured-logging/json] In addition, the TC39 proposal "Subsume JSON" made ECMAScript a strict JSON superset as of the language's 2019 revision.
[src:structured-logging/json] Various JSON parser implementations have suffered from denial-of-service attack and mass assignment vulnerability.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON is promoted as a low-overhead alternative to XML as both of these formats have widespread support for creation, reading, and decoding in the real-world situations where they are commonly used.
[src:structured-logging/json] XML has been used to describe structured data and to serialize objects.
[src:structured-logging/json] Various XML-based protocols exist to represent the same kind of data structures as JSON for the same kind of data interchange purposes.
[src:structured-logging/json] Data can be encoded in XML in several ways.
[src:structured-logging/json] The most expansive form using tag pairs results in a much larger (in character count) representation than JSON, but if data is stored in attributes and *short tag* form where the closing tag is replaced with `/>`, the representation is often about the same size as JSON or just a little larger.
[src:structured-logging/json] However, an XML attribute can only have a single value and each attribute can appear at most once on each element.
[src:structured-logging/json] XML separates data from metadata (via the use of elements and attributes), while JSON does not have such a concept.
[src:structured-logging/json] Another key difference is the addressing of values.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON has objects with a simple key-to-value mapping, whereas in XML addressing happens on *nodes*, each of which receives a unique ID via the XML processor.
[src:structured-logging/json] Additionally, the XML standard defines a common attribute `xml:id`, that can be used by the user, to set an ID explicitly.
[src:structured-logging/json] XML tag names cannot contain any of the characters !"#$%&'()*+,/;<=>?@[\]^`{|}~, nor a space character, and cannot begin with `-`, `.`, or a numeric digit, whereas JSON keys can (even if quotation mark and backslash must be escaped).
[src:structured-logging/json] XML values are strings of *characters*, with no built-in type safety.
[src:structured-logging/json] XML has the concept of schema, that permits strong typing, user-defined types, predefined tags, and formal structure, allowing for formal validation of an XML stream.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON has several types built-in and has a similar schema concept in JSON Schema.
[src:structured-logging/json] XML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:structured-logging/json] Support for comments and other features have been deemed useful, which has led to several nonstandard JSON supersets being created.
[src:structured-logging/json] Among them are HJSON, HOCON, and JSON5 (which despite its name, is not the fifth version of JSON).
[src:structured-logging/json] YAML version 1.2 is a superset of JSON; prior versions were not strictly compatible.
[src:structured-logging/json] For example, escaping a slash `/` with a backslash `\` is valid in JSON, but was not valid in YAML.
[src:structured-logging/json] YAML supports comments, while JSON does not.
[src:structured-logging/json] There is also an unrelated project called **CSON** ("Cursive Script Object Notation") that is more syntactically similar to JSON.
[src:structured-logging/json] JSON5 syntax is supported in some software as an extension of JSON syntax, for instance in SQLite.
[src:structured-logging/json] Several serialization formats have been built on or from the JSON specification.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] In computing, **logging** is the act of keeping a log of events that occur in a computer system, such as problems, errors or broad information on current operations.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] These events may occur in the operating system or in other software.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] A message or *log entry* is recorded for each such event.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] These log messages can then be used to monitor and understand the operation of the system, to debug problems, or during an audit.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Logging is particularly important in multi-user software, to have a central overview of the operation of the system.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] In the simplest case, messages are written to a file, called a *log file*.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Alternatively, the messages may be written to a dedicated logging system or to a log management software, where it is stored in a database or on a different computer system.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Specifically, a *transaction log* is a log of the communications between a system and the users of that system, or a data collection method that automatically captures the type, content, or time of transactions made by a person from a terminal with that system.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] For Web searching, a transaction log is an electronic record of interactions that have occurred during a searching episode between a Web search engine and users searching for information on that Web search engine.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Many operating systems, software frameworks and programs include a logging system.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] A widely used logging standard is Syslog, defined in IETF RFC 5424.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] The Syslog standard enables a dedicated, standardized subsystem to generate, filter, record, and analyze log messages.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] This relieves software developers of having to design and code their ad hoc logging systems.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] It can also be useful to combine log file entries from multiple sources.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] It is a different combination that may yield between with related events on different servers.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Other solutions employ network-wide querying and reporting.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Most database systems maintain some kind of *transaction log*, which are not mainly intended as an audit trail for later analysis, and are not intended to be human-readable.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] These logs record changes to the stored data to allow the database to recover from crashes or other data errors and maintain the stored data in a consistent state.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Thus, database systems usually have both general event logs and transaction logs.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] The use of data stored in transaction logs of Web search engines, Intranets, and websites can provide valuable insight into understanding the information-searching process of online searchers.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] This understanding can enlighten information system design, interface development, and devising the information architecture for content collections.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Message logs are almost universally plain text files, but IM and VoIP clients (which support textual chat, e.g.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Skype) might save them in HTML files or in a custom format to ease reading or enable encryption.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Instant messaging and VoIP clients often offer the chance to store encrypted logs to enhance the user's privacy.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] These logs require a password to be decrypted and viewed, and they are often handled by their respective writing application.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Some privacy focused messaging services, such as Signal, record minimal logs about users, limiting their information to connection times.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] A *server log* is a log file (or several files) automatically created and maintained by a server consisting of a list of activities it performed.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] A typical example is a web server log which maintains a history of page requests.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] The W3C maintains a standard format (the Common Log Format) for web server log files, but other proprietary formats exist.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Some servers can log information to computer readable formats (such as JSON) versus the human readable standard.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] More recent entries are typically appended to the end of the file.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Information about the request, including client IP address, request date/time, page requested, HTTP code, bytes served, user agent, and referrer are typically added.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] This data can be combined into a single file, or separated into distinct logs, such as an access log, error log, or referrer log.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] However, server logs typically do not collect user-specific information.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] These files are usually not accessible to general Internet users, only to the webmaster or other administrative person of an Internet service.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] A statistical analysis of the server log may be used to examine traffic patterns by time of day, day of week, referrer, or user agent.
[src:structured-logging/log-file] Efficient web site administration, adequate hosting resources and the fine tuning of sales efforts can be aided by analysis of the web server logs.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] In software engineering, more specifically in distributed computing, **observability** is the ability to collect data about programs' execution, modules' internal states, and the communication among components.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] To improve observability, software engineers use a wide range of logging and tracing techniques to gather telemetry information, and tools to analyze and use it.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Observability is foundational to site reliability engineering, as it is the first step in triaging a service outage.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] One of the goals of observability is to minimize the amount of prior knowledge needed to debug an issue.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] The term is borrowed from control theory, where the "observability" of a system measures how well its state can be determined from its outputs.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Similarly, software observability measures how well a system's state can be understood from the obtained telemetry (metrics, logs, traces, profiling).
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] The term is frequently referred to as its numeronym **o11y** (where 11 stands for the number of letters between the first letter and the last letter of the word).
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] This is similar to other computer science abbreviations such as i18n and l10n and k8s.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Observability and monitoring are sometimes used interchangeably.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] As tooling, commercial offerings and practices evolved in complexity, "monitoring" was re-branded as observability in order to differentiate new tools from the old.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] The terms are commonly contrasted in that systems are *monitored* using predefined sets of *telemetry*, and monitored systems may be *observable*.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Majors et al. suggest that engineering teams that only have monitoring tools end up relying on expert foreknowledge (seniority), whereas teams that have observability tools rely on exploratory analysis (curiosity).
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Observability relies on three main types of telemetry data: metrics, logs and traces.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Those are often referred to as "pillars of observability".
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] A metric is a point in time measurement (scalar) that represents some system state.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Monitoring tools are typically configured to emit alerts when certain metric values exceed set thresholds.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Thresholds are set based on knowledge about normal operating conditions and experience.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Metrics are typically tagged to facilitate grouping and searchability.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Application developers choose what kind of metrics to instrument their software with, before it is released.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] As a result, when a previously unknown issue is encountered, it is impossible to add new metrics without shipping new code.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Furthermore, their cardinality can quickly make the storage size of telemetry data prohibitively expensive.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Since metrics are cardinality-limited, they are often used to represent aggregate values (for example: average page load time, or 5-second average of the request rate).
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Without external context, it is impossible to correlate between events (such as user requests) and distinct metric values.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Logs, or log lines, are generally free-form, unstructured text blobs that are intended to be human readable.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Modern logging is structured to enable machine parsability.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] As with metrics, an application developer must instrument the application upfront and ship new code if different logging information is required.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Logs typically include a timestamp and severity level.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] An event (such as a user request) may be fragmented across multiple log lines and interweave with logs from concurrent events.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] A cloud native application is typically made up of distributed services which together fulfill a single request.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] A distributed trace is an interrelated series of discrete events (also called spans) that track the progression of a single user request.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] A trace shows the causal and temporal relationships between the services that interoperate to fulfill a request.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Instrumenting an application with traces means sending span information to a tracing backend.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] The tracing backend correlates the received spans to generate presentable traces.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] To be able to follow a request as it traverses multiple services, spans are labeled with unique identifiers that enable constructing a parent-child relationship between spans.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Span information is typically shared in the HTTP headers of outbound requests.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Continuous profiling is another telemetry type used to precisely determine how an application consumes resources.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] To be able to observe an application, telemetry about the application's behavior needs to be collected or exported.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Instrumentation means generating telemetry alongside the normal operation of the application.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Telemetry is then collected by an independent backend for later analysis.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Instrumentation can be automatic, or custom.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Automatic instrumentation offers blanket coverage and immediate value; custom instrumentation brings higher value but requires more intimate involvement with the instrumented application.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Instrumentation can be native - done in-code (modifying the code of the instrumented application) - or out-of-code (e.g. sidecar, eBPF).
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Verifying new features in production by shipping them together with custom instrumentation is a practice called "observability-driven development".
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Metrics, logs and traces are most commonly listed as the pillars of observability.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Self monitoring is a practice where observability stacks monitor each other, in order to reduce the risk of inconspicuous outages.
[src:structured-logging/observability-software] Self monitoring may be put in place in addition to high availability and redundancy to further avoid correlated failures.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] A **log** is a timestamped text record, either structured (recommended) or unstructured, with optional metadata.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Of all telemetry signals, logs have the biggest legacy.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Most programming languages have built-in logging capabilities or well-known, widely used logging libraries.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] OpenTelemetry provides a Logs API and SDK for producing log records, and language SDKs and logging bridges to integrate with existing logging frameworks.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Logs are anything you send through a Logging Provider, and events are a special type of logs.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Not all logs are events, but all events are logs.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] The Logs API is public and can be used directly by application code or indirectly via existing logging libraries and bridges.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] OpenTelemetry is designed to work with the logs you already produce, offering tools to correlate logs with other signals, add contextual attributes, and normalize different sources into a common representation for processing and export.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] The first step in adopting OpenTelemetry frequently involves deploying a Collector as a general-purposes logging agent.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] In applications, OpenTelemetry logs are created with any logging library or built-in logging capabilities.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] When you add autoinstrumentation or activate an SDK, OpenTelemetry will automatically correlate your existing logs with any active trace and span, wrapping the log body with their IDs.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] In other words, OpenTelemetry automatically correlates your logs and traces.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Logs are a stable signal in the OpenTelemetry specification.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] OpenTelemetry accepts any log format, but not all formats are equally useful for analysis.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] The following section explains the differences between structured, semistructured, and unstructured logs.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Important: a log encoded as JSON is not automatically “structured” in the sense of having a stable schema —it may be semistructured.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Structured logs imply a consistent schema or well-defined typed fields that downstream processing can reliably depend on.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] A structured log is a log with a defined, consistent schema or typed fields that downstream systems can reliably parse and interpret.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] The textual encoding can be JSON, protobuf, or another format, but what makes a log structured is the presence of a stable schema (field names, types, and semantics), not merely that it is valid JSON.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] It is also common to encounter hybrid or extended formats (for example, CLF fields combined with a trailing JSON blob).
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] In those cases, parse or extract the parts you need into a normalized record so downstream tooling can analyze them consistently.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] The `filelogreceiver` in the OpenTelemetry Collector provides helpers to parse mixed formats.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Structured logs are preferred in production because their stable schema makes them straightforward to validate, parse, correlate with traces and metrics, and analyze at scale.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Unstructured logs are logs that don’t follow a consistent structure.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] They may be more human-readable, and are often used in development.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] However, it is not preferred to use unstructured logs for production observability purposes, since they are much more difficult to parse and analyze at scale.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] It is possible to store and analyze Unstructured logs in production, although you may need to do substantial work to parse or otherwise pre-process them to be machine-readable.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] For example, the above three logs will require a regular expression to parse their timestamps and custom parsers to consistently extract the bodies of the log message.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] This will typically be necessary for a logging backend to know how to sort and organize the logs by timestamp.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Although it’s possible to parse unstructured logs for analysis purposes, doing this may be more work than switching to structured logging, such as via a standard logging framework in your applications.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Semistructured logs include machine-readable key/value pairs or delimited fields but do not guarantee a stable schema across emitters.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Examples include key=value logging (shown below) or JSON blobs where field names and types vary between messages.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Semistructured logs are often easier to parse than unstructured logs but may still require processing and normalization before analysis.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Semistructured logs may require mapping and type coercion during ingestion to be fully useful for downstream analysis.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] The following lists of concepts and components power OpenTelemetry’s logging support.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] As an application developer, the **Logs Bridge API** should not be called by you directly, as it is provided for logging library authors to build log appenders / bridges.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Instead, you just use your preferred logging library and configure it to use a log appender (or log bridge) that is able to emit logs into an OpenTelemetry LogRecordExporter.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] OpenTelemetry language SDKs offer this functionality.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] A Logger Provider (sometimes called `LoggerProvider`) is a factory for `Logger`s.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] In most cases, the Logger Provider is initialized once and its lifecycle matches the application’s lifecycle.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Logger Provider initialization also includes Resource and Exporter initialization.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] Log Record Exporters send log records to a consumer.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] This consumer can be standard output for debugging and development-time, the OpenTelemetry Collector, or any open source or vendor backend of your choice.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] A log record represents the recording of an event.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] For more details on log records and log fields, see Logs Data Model.
[src:structured-logging/signals-logs] To learn more about logs in OpenTelemetry, see the logs specification.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] In computing, **syslog** (/ˈsɪslɒɡ/) is a standard for message logging.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] It allows separation of the software that generates messages, the system that stores them, and the software that reports and analyzes them.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Each message is labeled with a facility code, indicating the type of system generating the message, and is assigned a severity level.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Computer system designers may use syslog for system management and security auditing as well as general informational, analysis, and debugging messages.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] A wide variety of devices, such as printers, routers, and message receivers across many platforms, use the syslog standard.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] This permits the consolidation of logging data from different types of systems in a central repository.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Implementations of syslog exist for many operating systems.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where a **syslog server** listens for and logs messages coming from clients.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Syslog was developed in the 1980s by Eric Allman as part of the Sendmail project.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] It was readily adopted by other applications and has since become the standard logging solution on Unix-like systems.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] A variety of implementations also exist on other operating systems and it is commonly found in network devices, such as routers.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Syslog originally functioned as a de facto standard, without any authoritative published specification, and many implementations existed, some of which were incompatible.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The Internet Engineering Task Force documented the status quo in RFC 3164 in August 2001.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] It was standardized by RFC 5424 in March 2009.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Various companies have attempted to claim patents for specific aspects of syslog implementations.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] This has had little effect on the use and standardization of the protocol.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The information provided by the originator of a syslog message includes the facility code and the severity level.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The syslog software adds information to the information header before passing the entry to the syslog receiver.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Such components include an originator process ID, a timestamp, and the hostname or IP address of the device.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] A facility code is used to specify the type of system that is logging the message.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Messages with different facilities may be handled differently.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The mapping between facility code and keyword is not uniform in different operating systems and syslog implementations.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The meaning of severity levels other than *Emergency* and *Debug* are relative to the application.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] For example, if the purpose of the system is to process transactions to update customer account balance information, an error in the final step should be assigned *Alert* level.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] However, an error occurring in an attempt to display the ZIP code of the customer may be assigned *Error* or even *Warning* level.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The server process that handles display of messages usually includes all lower (more severe) levels when the display of less severe levels is requested.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] That is, if messages are separated by individual severity, a *Warning* level entry will also be included when filtering for *Notice*, *Info* and *Debug* messages.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] In RFC 3164, the message component (known as MSG) was specified as having these fields: *TAG*, which should be the name of the program or process that generated the message, and *CONTENT* which contains the details of the message.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Described in RFC 5424, "MSG is what was called CONTENT in RFC 3164.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The TAG is now part of the header, but not as a single field.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The TAG has been split into APP-NAME, PROCID, and MSGID.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] This does not totally resemble the usage of TAG, but provides the same functionality for most of the cases." Popular syslog tools such as NXLog, Rsyslog conform to this new standard.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The content field should be encoded in a UTF-8 character set and octet values in the traditional ASCII control character range should be avoided.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Generated log messages may be directed to various destinations, including: console, files, remote syslog servers, or relays.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Most implementations provide a command line utility, often called *logger*, as well as a software library, to send messages to the log.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] To display and monitor the collected logs, one needs to use a client application or access the log file directly on the system.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The basic command line tools are tail and grep.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The log servers can be configured to send the logs over the network (in addition to the local files).
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Some implementations include reporting programs for filtering and displaying syslog messages.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] When operating over a network, syslog uses a client-server architecture where the server listens on a well-known or registered port for protocol requests from clients.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Historically the most common transport layer protocol for network logging has been User Datagram Protocol (UDP), with the server listening on port 514.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Because UDP lacks congestion control mechanisms, Transmission Control Protocol (TCP) port 6514 is used; Transport Layer Security is also required in implementations and recommended for general use.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Since each process, application, and operating system was written independently, there is little uniformity to the payload of the log message.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] For this reason, no assumption is made about its formatting or contents.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] A syslog message is formatted (RFC 5424 gives the Augmented Backus–Naur form (ABNF) definition), but its MSG field is not.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The network protocol is simplex communication, with no means of acknowledging the delivery to the originator.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Various groups are working on draft standards detailing the use of syslog for more than just network and security event logging, such as its proposed application within the healthcare environment.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Regulations, such as the Sarbanes–Oxley Act, PCI DSS, HIPAA, and many others, require organizations to implement comprehensive security measures, which often include collecting and analyzing logs from many different sources.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The syslog format has proven effective in consolidating logs, as there are many open-source and proprietary tools for reporting and analysis of these logs.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Utilities exist for conversion from Windows Event Log and other log formats to syslog.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] Managed Security Service Providers attempt to apply analytical techniques and artificial intelligence algorithms to detect patterns and alert customers to problems.
[src:structured-logging/syslog] The Syslog protocol is defined by Request for Comments (RFC) documents published by the Internet Engineering Task Force (Internet standards).
